Well, this is impossible to un-see. From Vlad … 8d Jennifer finally leaving as Johnson was dressing (4)[ wordplay: office once held by Boris Johnson (‘as Johnson was’), without final letter of JENNIFER (‘Jennifer finally leaving’) ][ MAYOR – R ][ definition: dressing ] … an unpleasant reminder that we still don’t know how happy the ending of the Jennifer Arcuri saga is. Meanwhile, this one-across in a themed puzzle from Morph … 1ac/11ac/1d When results turn bad, they’ll run company on short-term basis? (4-7,7)[ cryptic definition ] … for FAIR-WEATHER FRIENDS reappears later in a clue … 14ac/16ac Trump’s nemesis who’ll produce denials, getting no support from 1,11,1? (6,7)[ wordplay: anagram of (‘who’ll produce’) DENIALS, preceded by adjective describing condition that fair-weather friends are unlikely to support ][ DANIELS preceded by STORMY ][ definition: Trump’s nemesis ] … for STORMY DANIELS. And a prize puzzle (with its own stunning theme) from Brendan for which the annotated solution is now available contains a timely, novel cryptic device … 24d Authentic German dramatist affected by Brexit? (4)[ wordplay: name of German dramatist, without BR (affected by Brexit) ][ BRECHT – BR ][ definition: authentic ] … to clue ECHT – which reminds me, via the first puzzle in our American-style series, that we’re due another one soon. I’ll construct it if no one else does? Last week we mentioned the very proper inclusion in Macquarie Dictionary’s Words of the Year of “robodebt”, a grim phenomenon that the Aussie Guardian has been following doggedly. This month in the quiptic – the Guardian’s stepping stone for beginners and those in a hurry – Anto has given us this clue … 5d Key line in legal contract (6)[ wordplay: computer key + synonym for ‘line’ ][ ESC + ROW ][ definition: legal contract ] … for ESCROW, a word which goes way back, back as far as “scroll”, and is good friends with “shred”, while Hectence has clued … 19d Forbid taking krone raised by head of trust that’s insolvent (8)[ wordplay: synonym for ‘ban’ + abbrev. for ‘krone’ + synonym for ‘raised’ + first letter (‘head’) of TRUST ][ BAN + KR + UP + T ][ definition: insolvent ] … BANKRUPT. That term, excitingly, comes to us simultaneously from the French “bancque roupte” and the Italian “banca rotta”; the OED goes on: The Italian expression is said to refer to a former custom of breaking the stall of a trader who had become insolvent Yes indeed, it “is said to” refer to that. Here’s one of the people who said that … … and his name is Samuel Johnson. To fail to mention the man whose dictionary precedes your own by 173 years: is this how lexicographers throw shade? In any event, our next challenge concerns a word that famously combines “dead” and “pledge”: reader, how would you clue MORTGAGE? Thanks for your clues for PLAGIARIST. The audacity award goes to DeetotheGee for the baroque “Mountain climbing on Garfield Peak, I met timeless artist; but his ideas were not his own”. And for inside-baseball clues, I was tickled for a prolonged time by Peshwari’s “He enjoys cribbage and asparagus, freaked the Americans out and occasionally accommodated last idealist in Tory leadership” as well as Wellywearer2’s “Cribbage exponent?” What is it about this entry that tempts us towards the cryptic definition? Whatever the answer, the runners-up are Alberyalbery’s “He forged a career in writing?” and Porcia’s “One who takes credit for recycling paper?” and the winner is 10FootClaudicant’s “Copywriter?” Kludos to 10FootClaudicant Croquem; please leave entries for this fortnight’s competition and your picks from the broadsheet cryptics below. An appearance from Slormgorm in the Financial Times is always welcome. Case in point: this clue … 17ac It’s a job for a cold and noble soldier (10)[ wordplay: A (‘a’) + abbrev. for ‘cold’ + synonym for ‘noble’ + what ‘soldier’ is example of ][ A + C + COUNT + ANT ][ definition: it’s a job ] … for ACCOUNTANT. Ka-ching.